\begin_layout Paragraph
Spot matching process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three parties involved in the matching process: sellers, buyers,
 and the platform itself.
 Time is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is mass 1 of sellers, who always stay on the platform; they never
 leave or arrive.
 At each moment it time, a seller is either available or busy.
 An available seller is presented with a sequence of buyers at a Poisson
 rate, and decides whether to accept or reject them in order to maximize
 his average profit flow.
 Busy sellers do not receive requests from buyers.
 When an available seller accepts a buyer, he becomes busy for time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 When this time elapses, the seller becomes available again.
 The fact that sellers become unavailable after each match is the main source
 of matching friction.
 In what follows, I also refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as the seller capacity constraint, because the higher value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the fewer buyers the seller can match with during the same period of time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a continuum of potential buyers, who gradually arrive at flow rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

: Within time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

, mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta dt$
\end_inset

 of buyers arrive at the platform.
 Each new buyer contacts one of the available sellers.
 The seller is chosen uniformly at random from the pool of available sellers.
 If the buyer is accepted, he stays while the match lasts; otherwise, he
 leaves the platform.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\tau<1$
\end_inset

, which implies that collectively, it is physically possible for sellers
