\begin_layout Paragraph
Steady-state distribution of sellers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matching process is the dynamic system in which sellers become repeatedly
 busy and available.
 A steady state of the matching process is characterized by the fraction
 of available sellers of every type and their acceptance rates.
 Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 be the 
\emph on
acceptance rate
\emph default
, the fraction of buyers accepted by type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(y)$
\end_inset

 be the
\emph on
 utilization rate, the
\emph default
 fraction of type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers who are busy.
 Denote the average utilization rate by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}:=\int_{Y}\rho(y)dG(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the total mass of sellers is 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\brho$
\end_inset

 is also the mass of busy sellers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a steady state, the flow of sellers who form new matches is equal to
 the flow of sellers who return to waiting.
 The flow of new matches is equal to the product of the buyer flow that
 type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers receive and type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers' acceptance rate.
 Since buyers distribute uniformly across the available sellers, the buyer
 flow to type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\frac{(1-\rho(y))g(y)}{1-\bar{\rho}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the flow of new matches is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\frac{(1-\rho(y))g(y)}{1-\bar{\rho}}\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

.
 The flow of returning sellers is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\rho(y)/\tau$
\end_inset

, because the mass of busy type-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 sellers is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\rho(y)$
\end_inset

 and matches last time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
