\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Equilibrium-exists-and"

\end_inset

A steady-state equilibrium exists, and it is unique up to the acceptance
 of marginal buyers in the following sense: If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma^{i},\brho^{i})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

, are two steady-state equilibria, then (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\brho^{1}=\brho^{2}$
\end_inset

, and (2) for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{1}(\cdot,y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}(\cdot,y)$
\end_inset

 coincide except on 
\begin_inset Formula $\{s\colon\pi(s,y)=\tau V(y)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove this result, first, I show that for an arbitrary vector of acceptance
 rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

, there is a unique steady-state value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\brho$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:rho-and-monotonicities"

\end_inset

).
 Then, the average utilization rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is increasing and continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(y)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 The uniqueness of the equilibrium follows from monotonicity of the reaction
 curves of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
